{"title_page": "Ditmas (song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Ditmas\n| cover      = DitmasMumford.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Mumford & Sons]]\n| album      = [[Wilder Mind]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2015|09|11|df=yes}}\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2014\u201315 at [[AIR Studios]] ([[London]])\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Indie rock]]|[[alternative rock]]}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=38}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Island Records|Island]]|[[Glassnote Records|Glassnote]]|Gentlemen of the Road}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Ted Dwane]]|[[Ben Lovett (British musician)|Ben Lovett]]|[[Winston Marshall]]|[[Marcus Mumford]]}}\n| producer   = [[James Ford (musician)|James Ford]]\n| prev_title = [[The Wolf (Mumford & Sons song)|The Wolf]]\n| prev_year  = 2015\n| next_title = [[Tompkins Square Park (song)|Tompkins Square Park]]\n| next_year  = 2015\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|cOBPiOdyGEM|\"Ditmas\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Ditmas'''\" is a song by the band [[Mumford & Sons]] from their third studio album ''[[Wilder Mind]]''. It was released worldwide as the third single from the album on September 11, 2015, and was sent to American [[Alternative rock|alternative]] stations on 17 November 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allaccess.com/alternative/future-releases |title=Alternative Future Releases |publisher=All Access Music Group |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6d4mC91Ag?url=http://www.allaccess.com/alternative/future-releases |archivedate=November 16, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe title of the song stems from [[Ditmas Park, Brooklyn]] in [[New York City]]; Ditmas Park is the location of [[The National (band)|The National]] guitarist [[Aaron Dessner]]'s studio where most of the album was written and demo'd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mumfordandsons.com/news/ditmas-official-video/|title=Ditmas - Official Video - Mumford & Sons|publisher=[[Mumford and Sons]]|date=23 July 2015|accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> The song is a representation of the change in the band's sound, most noticeably less usage of the [[banjo]] and more utilization of electric [[Musical instrument|instruments]]. The song is described as a [[breakup]] song.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/music/wilder-mind-is-the-de-mumfordization-of-mumford-and-sons/2015/05/04/414e768c-f26c-11e4-84a6-6d7c67c50db0_story.html</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[music video]] for the song showcases the relationship between a Ukrainian [[Cossack]] and his [[horse]]. Directed by [[Alex Southam]], the video was shot in [[Kyiv]], [[Ukraine]].<ref>https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/mumford-sons-saddle-up-in-rousing-ditmas-video-20150723</ref> The band is also seen performing the song throughout the video. \n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2015)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br /> position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/aria-singles-justin-bieber-what-do-you-mean-keeps-top-spot-20150919|title=ARIA Singles: Justin Bieber 'What Do You Mean' Keeps Top Spot|publisher=Noise11|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|date=19 September 2015|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref>\n| 80\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders Tip|17|artist=Mumford & Sons|song=Ditmas|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 September 2015}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland|99|year=2015|week=38|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 September 2015}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|83|date=2015-09-24|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 September 2015}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrocksongs|38|artist=Mumford & Sons|artistid=311935|accessdate=December 21, 2015|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardadultalternativesongs|3|artist=Mumford & Sons|artistid=311935|accessdate=December 21, 2015|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardalternativesongs|15|artist=Mumford & Sons|artistid=311935|accessdate=December 21, 2015|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrockairplay|15|artist=Mumford & Sons|artistid=311935|accessdate=December 21, 2015|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Mumford & Sons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ditmas (Mumford and Sons song)}}\n[[Category:Mumford & Sons songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ben Lovett (British musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ted Dwane]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Winston Marshall]]\n[[Category:2015 songs]]\n[[Category:2015 singles]]\n[[Category:Music videos shot in Ukraine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Ditmas\n| cover      = DitmasMumford.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Mumford & Sons]]\n| album      = [[Wilder Mind]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2015|09|11|df=yes}}\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2014\u201315 at [[AIR Studios]] ([[London]])\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Indie rock]]|[[alternative rock]]}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=38}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Island Records|Island]]|[[Glassnote Records|Glassnote]]|Gentlemen of the Road}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Ted Dwane]]|[[Ben Lovett (British musician)|Ben Lovett]]|[[Winston Marshall]]|[[Marcus Mumford]]}}\n| producer   = [[James Ford (musician)|James Ford]]\n| prev_title = [[The Wolf (Mumford & Sons song)|The Wolf]]\n| prev_year  = 2015\n| next_title = [[Tompkins Square Park (song)|Tompkins Square Park]]\n| next_year  = 2015\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|cOBPiOdyGEM|\"Ditmas\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Ditmas'''\" is a song by the band [[Mumford & Sons]] from their third studio album ''[[Wilder Mind]]''. It was released worldwide as the third single from the album on September 11, 2015, and was sent to American [[Alternative rock|alternative]] stations on 17 November 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allaccess.com/alternative/future-releases |title=Alternative Future Releases |publisher=All Access Music Group |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6d4mC91Ag?url=http://www.allaccess.com/alternative/future-releases |archivedate=November 16, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe title of the song stems from [[Ditmas Park, Brooklyn]] in [[New York City]]; The band recorded the song in that area. Ditmas Park was also the location of the studio of [[The National (band)|The National]]'s guitarist, [[Aaron Dessner]], where most of the album was recorded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mumfordandsons.com/news/ditmas-official-video/|title=Ditmas - Official Video - Mumford & Sons|publisher=[[Mumford and Sons]]|date=23 July 2015|accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> The song is a representation of the change in the band's sound, most noticeably less usage of the [[banjo]] and more utilization of electric [[Musical instrument|instruments]]. The song can be described as a [[break-up]] song.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/music/wilder-mind-is-the-de-mumfordization-of-mumford-and-sons/2015/05/04/414e768c-f26c-11e4-84a6-6d7c67c50db0_story.html</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[music video]] for the song showcases the relationship between a Ukrainian [[Cossack]] and his [[horse]]. Directed by [[Alex Southam]], the video was shot in [[Kyiv]], [[Ukraine]].<ref>https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/mumford-sons-saddle-up-in-rousing-ditmas-video-20150723</ref> The band is also seen performing the song throughout the video. \n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2015)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br /> position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/aria-singles-justin-bieber-what-do-you-mean-keeps-top-spot-20150919|title=ARIA Singles: Justin Bieber 'What Do You Mean' Keeps Top Spot|publisher=Noise11|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|date=19 September 2015|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref>\n| 80\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders Tip|17|artist=Mumford & Sons|song=Ditmas|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 September 2015}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland|99|year=2015|week=38|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 September 2015}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|83|date=2015-09-24|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 September 2015}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrocksongs|38|artist=Mumford & Sons|artistid=311935|accessdate=December 21, 2015|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardadultalternativesongs|3|artist=Mumford & Sons|artistid=311935|accessdate=December 21, 2015|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardalternativesongs|15|artist=Mumford & Sons|artistid=311935|accessdate=December 21, 2015|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrockairplay|15|artist=Mumford & Sons|artistid=311935|accessdate=December 21, 2015|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Mumford & Sons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ditmas (Mumford and Sons song)}}\n[[Category:Mumford & Sons songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ben Lovett (British musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ted Dwane]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Winston Marshall]]\n[[Category:2015 songs]]\n[[Category:2015 singles]]\n[[Category:Music videos shot in Ukraine]]\n", "name_user": "TheMajorLift", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ditmas_(song)"}
{"title_page": "Sharif Sabir", "text_new": "{{Hatnote|For other possible meanings see [[Sabir (disambiguation)]]}}\n{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n  <!-- The Infobox_Biography entries are examples only-->\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sharif Sabir <br />{{nq|\u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0635\u0627\u0628\u0631 }}\n| image              = File:Sharif sabir.jpg\n| image_size         = 180px\n| caption            = Sharif Sabir in 2010\n| birth_date         = 18th May 1928\n| birth_place        = Pakki Saraan (near [[Lahore]]), district [[Sheikhupura]]\n| death_date         = 1st October 2015 (age 87)\n| death_place        = [[Narang Mandi]], [[Punjab]]\n| occupation         = [[Philosopher]], [[Poet]], [[Punjabi Literature]]\n| spouse             = Zubaidah Akhter (died 2000)\n| parents            = \n| website            = http://msharifsabir.com\n| children           = Lozina Sharif Zadi<br>Samir Shaur Ahmed<br>Azam Saud Ahmed<br>Fawiz Junood Ahmed<br>Noshina Sharif Zadi<br>Wasiq Aqood Ahmed (died 1986)\n}}\n\n'''Shaikh Muhammad Sharif Sabir''' ([[Urdu language|Urdu]]: \u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0635\u0627\u0628\u0631\u202c\u200e;  18 May 1928 \u2013 1 October 2015), better known as '''Sharif Sabir''', was a Pakistani-Punjabi scholar, poet, researcher and educationist who is widely known for editing the most authentic version of [[Heer Ranjha|Heer Waris Shah]] published in 1985. It took him over ten years to complete this work. Earlier, he had already written a book of poetry and edited ''[[Puran Bhagat]]'' of [[Qadir Yar]], and translated parts of ''[[Gulistan (book)|Gulistan]]'' and ''[[Bustan (book)|Bustan]]'' of [[Saadi Shirazi]] into Punjabi'''.''' He edited [[Sultan Bahu]]\u2019s poetry collection ''Abiat-e-Bahu'', [[Mian Muhammad Bakhsh|Mian Mohammad Bakhsh]]'s monumental work of ''[[Prince Saiful Malook and Badri Jamala|Saiful Muluk]]'', the poetry of [[Bulleh Shah]] and had just completed editing of the poetry of [[Fariduddin Ganjshakar|Baba Farid]] before his demise. Being also a scholar of Persian and Arabic, he undertook a Herculean translation of [[Ali Hujwiri|Ali Hajweri Gunj Bakhsh]]\u2019s ''[[Kashf ul Mahjoob]]'' from Persian to Urdu. He was commissioned by the [[Punjab Auqaf and Religious Affairs Department|Punjab Auqaf Department]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://tns.thenews.com.pk/portrait-of-sheikh-sharif-sabir-son-soil/|title=Portrait of a son of soil|last=Editor|first=T. N. S.|date=2015-10-25|website=TNS - The News on Sunday|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n<!-- [[Image:Subject's earliest portrait.ext|thumb|right|Photo caption]] -->\nHe was born into a poor household in Pakki Saraan (near [[Lahore]]), [[Sheikhupura District]], [[Pakistan]]. Unlike his age fellows, he spent most of his teenage years working and earning to pay for his tuitions. He started his career as an English language teacher in a government school. While teaching English to elementary classes, he privately did a Masters in [[Persian language|Persian]] and went on to teach [[Persian language|Persian]] and [[Urdu]] at Lahore\u2019s [[Central Model School, Lahore|Central Model School]]. He was promoted to be a language specialist and taught at the Central Training College. He became a headmaster before the Punjab government and the Waris Shah Academy got his services on deputation to complete his research on [[Heer Ranjha|Heer Waris Shah]]. Although he took his retirement in the 1980s, he continued his research and published a number of books in later years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1210632|title=Punjabi poet, researcher Sharif Sabir laid to rest|last=Report|first=Dawn|date=2015-10-03|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Life Long Research - Editing of Heer Waris Shah==\nSharif Sabir was posted for two years at the Waris Shah Memorial Committee (WSMC), which was established by the cultural department of Punjab. Here, he was tasked to build [[Waris Shah]]\u2019s [[Shrine]] in [[Jandiala Sher Khan]] and also publish an authentic [[Heer Ranjha|Heer Waris Shah]] text. By the time his posting began, Sabir had already spent 12 years on his Heer research. During his posting, apart from reviewing his previous work he was also able to access one 1821 hand-written manuscript that according to him was found in [[Patiala]], [[Punjab, India|Punjab]]. He traveled all over Punjab, especially to places where the old dialect was still spoken. He went to see the traders and the craftsmen to understand the terms used by [[Waris Shah]] while describing their trades and professions; he went to snake-charmers to learn about snakes; he visited scholars of folklore and consulted many a book on mythology to understand the background of the myths and the stories alluded to by [[Waris Shah]].\n\nWSMC published Sabir\u2019s edited Heer in 1985. Sabir later in 2006, printed a revised and updated edition with the help of Progressive Books, [[Lahore]]. The most striking feature of his Heer compilation is that he has provided the meanings of difficult words and details about people and places that appear in [[Waris Shah]]\u2019s epic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://apnaorg.com/columns/mahmood-awan/column-36.html|title=250 years of Heer Waris Shah|website=apnaorg.com|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\n==Marriage and children==\nHe was married to Zubaidah Akhter and was a loving husband and a caring father. He was blessed with his four sons and two daughters. One of his sons died as a teenager in a terrible accident while playing with fire. He was severely burnt and was admitted in the hospital for just shy of one year before his death. Of the other three sons, one went on to become an army officer, another a professional banker and the third an engineer. Daughters are married too. All of the kids emigrated to the [[United States]] in 2008. He never wanted to live anywhere else but with his Punjabi community, however he was convinced by his kids to live with them in the [[United States]]. He visited them in 2013 and stayed with his children and grandchildren for two years. In 2015, he decided to go back to his village in [[Pakistan]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Death and afterward==\nDeath finally caught up with him in the village when he developed a chest infection. He was brought to [[Fatima Memorial Hospital]] in [[Lahore]] but it was too late. At the hospital, after his operation, he was not able to recognize people nor could he speak well. He was buried near a friendly saint\u2019s tomb in Narang Mandi. May God bless his soul.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Published works==\nAll the books Sharif Sabir has edited -- [[Heer Ranjha|Heer Waris Shah]], complete poetry of [[Bulleh Shah]] and [[Sultan Bahu]] and [[Prince Saiful Malook and Badri Jamala|Saiful Malook]] of [[Mian Muhammad Bakhsh]] -- have one outstanding feature in common. All of them carry a glossary of difficult words. No other book in [[Punjabi literature|Punjabi Literature]], other than those written on the [[Guru Granth Sahib]], contain comprehensive glossaries like the ones found in the works he has edited. Following is a list of books he has authored, edited or translated:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Works by Sharif Sabir\n!Book\n!Original Author\n!Sabir's Contribution\n!Year\n|-\n|Kalaam\n|[[Fariduddin Ganjshakar|Baba Farid]]\n|Edited (Due Publication)\n|\n|-\n|[[Prince Saiful Malook and Badri Jamala|Saiful Malook]]\n|[[Mian Muhammad Bakhsh]]\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLVnJKcFB6dkdYM0E/view Edited]\n|\n|-\n|[[Heer Ranjha|Heer Waris Shah]]\n|[[Waris Shah]]\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLVVMtN2dpQXhaTlk/view Edited]\n|\n|-\n|[https://www.sultanbahoo.net/abyat/ Abyat-e-Bahoo]\n|[[Sultan Bahu]]\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLN3NlVlc2azhfMEU/view Edited]\n|\n|-\n|[[Bulleh Shah]]\n|[[Bulleh Shah]]\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/1mLoCPnL1tt9GBJzzScwTpRieyUYQTODR/view Edited]\n|\n|-\n|Farsi Kalam\n|[https://www.facebook.com/Hafizsufimuhammadafzal/ Sufi Muhammad Afzal Faqeer]\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLZG5uZDdfOUVhTW8/view Translated]\n|\n|-\n|[[Puran Bhagat]]\n|[[Qadir Yar]]\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLQ042bXFaZ0M2ZDQ/view Translated]\n|\n|-\n|[[Kashf ul Mahjoob]]\n|[[Ali Hujwiri]]\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLYmQ4cWh1cmtjR1E/view Translated]\n|\n|-\n|[[Gulistan (book)|Gulistan]] and [[Bustan (book)|Bustan]]\n|[[Saadi Shirazi]]\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLcVY2QXhBQndFWFU/view Translated]\n|\n|-\n|Hatkoray\n|Sharif Sabir\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLdFpNc05xQzlVVDg/view Authored]\n|\n|-\n|Baghawat\n|Sharif Sabir\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLRnBfRmZaV2lyWHc/view Authored]\n|\n|-\n|Punjabi Drama\n|Sharif Sabir\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLZEZpZG9hcGs2Q3M/view Authored]\n|\n|-\n|Autobiography\n|Sharif Sabir\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLQVRjQ1FSMGFwX1k/view Authored]\n|\n|}\n\n==Honours, decorations, awards and distinctions==\nHe was given the [[Pride of Performance]] and a paltry sum of Rs 70,000 for his monumental work [[Heer Ranjha|Heer Waris Shah]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://apnaorg.com/prose-content/articles-by-writers/Nadir-Ali/page-1/article-7/index.html|title=Victim of ignorance|website=apnaorg.com|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLQVRjQ1FSMGFwX1k/view Autobiography in Punjabi]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sabir, Sharif}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Pakistani philosophers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani poets]]\n[[Category:Punjabi poets]]\n", "text_old": "{{Hatnote|For other possible meanings see [[Sabir (disambiguation)]]}}\n\n  <!-- The Infobox_Biography entries are examples only-->\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sharif Sabir <br />{{nq|\u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0635\u0627\u0628\u0631 }}\n| image              = File:Sharif sabir.jpg\n| image_size         = 180px\n| caption            = Sharif Sabir in 2010\n| birth_date         = 18th May 1928\n| birth_place        = Pakki Saraan (near [[Lahore]]), district [[Sheikhupura]]\n| death_date         = 1st October 2015 (age 87)\n| death_place        = [[Narang Mandi]], [[Punjab]]\n| occupation         = [[Philosopher]], [[Poet]], [[Punjabi Literature]]\n| spouse             = Zubaidah Akhter (died 2000)\n| parents            = \n| website            = http://msharifsabir.com\n| children           = Lozina Sharif Zadi<br>Samir Shaur Ahmed<br>Azam Saud Ahmed<br>Fawiz Junood Ahmed<br>Noshina Sharif Zadi<br>Wasiq Aqood Ahmed (died 1986)\n}}\n\n'''Shaikh Muhammad Sharif Sabir''' ([[Urdu language|Urdu]]: \u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0635\u0627\u0628\u0631\u202c\u200e;  18 May 1928 \u2013 1 October 2015), better known as '''Sharif Sabir''', was a Pakistani-Punjabi scholar, poet, researcher and educationist who is widely known for editing the most authentic version of [[Heer Ranjha|Heer Waris Shah]] published in 1985. It took him over ten years to complete this work. Earlier, he had already written a book of poetry and edited ''[[Puran Bhagat]]'' of [[Qadir Yar]], and translated parts of ''[[Gulistan (book)|Gulistan]]'' and ''[[Bustan (book)|Bustan]]'' of [[Saadi Shirazi]] into Punjabi'''.''' He edited [[Sultan Bahu]]\u2019s poetry collection ''Abiat-e-Bahu'', [[Mian Muhammad Bakhsh|Mian Mohammad Bakhsh]]'s monumental work of ''[[Prince Saiful Malook and Badri Jamala|Saiful Muluk]]'', the poetry of [[Bulleh Shah]] and had just completed editing of the poetry of [[Fariduddin Ganjshakar|Baba Farid]] before his demise. Being also a scholar of Persian and Arabic, he undertook a Herculean translation of [[Ali Hujwiri|Ali Hajweri Gunj Bakhsh]]\u2019s ''[[Kashf ul Mahjoob]]'' from Persian to Urdu. He was commissioned by the [[Punjab Auqaf and Religious Affairs Department|Punjab Auqaf Department]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://tns.thenews.com.pk/portrait-of-sheikh-sharif-sabir-son-soil/|title=Portrait of a son of soil|last=Editor|first=T. N. S.|date=2015-10-25|website=TNS - The News on Sunday|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n<!-- [[Image:Subject's earliest portrait.ext|thumb|right|Photo caption]] -->\nHe was born into a poor household in Pakki Saraan (near [[Lahore]]), [[Sheikhupura District]], [[Pakistan]]. Unlike his age fellows, he spent most of his teenage years working and earning to pay for his tuitions. He started his career as an English language teacher in a government school. While teaching English to elementary classes, he privately did a Masters in [[Persian language|Persian]] and went on to teach [[Persian language|Persian]] and [[Urdu]] at Lahore\u2019s [[Central Model School, Lahore|Central Model School]]. He was promoted to be a language specialist and taught at the Central Training College. He became a headmaster before the Punjab government and the Waris Shah Academy got his services on deputation to complete his research on [[Heer Ranjha|Heer Waris Shah]]. Although he took his retirement in the 1980s, he continued his research and published a number of books in later years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1210632|title=Punjabi poet, researcher Sharif Sabir laid to rest|last=Report|first=Dawn|date=2015-10-03|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Life Long Research - Editing of Heer Waris Shah==\nSharif Sabir was posted for two years at the Waris Shah Memorial Committee (WSMC), which was established by the cultural department of Punjab. Here, he was tasked to build [[Waris Shah]]\u2019s [[Shrine]] in [[Jandiala Sher Khan]] and also publish an authentic [[Heer Ranjha|Heer Waris Shah]] text. By the time his posting began, Sabir had already spent 12 years on his Heer research. During his posting, apart from reviewing his previous work he was also able to access one 1821 hand-written manuscript that according to him was found in [[Patiala]], [[Punjab, India|Punjab]]. He traveled all over Punjab, especially to places where the old dialect was still spoken. He went to see the traders and the craftsmen to understand the terms used by [[Waris Shah]] while describing their trades and professions; he went to snake-charmers to learn about snakes; he visited scholars of folklore and consulted many a book on mythology to understand the background of the myths and the stories alluded to by [[Waris Shah]].\n\nWSMC published Sabir\u2019s edited Heer in 1985. Sabir later in 2006, printed a revised and updated edition with the help of Progressive Books, [[Lahore]]. The most striking feature of his Heer compilation is that he has provided the meanings of difficult words and details about people and places that appear in [[Waris Shah]]\u2019s epic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://apnaorg.com/columns/mahmood-awan/column-36.html|title=250 years of Heer Waris Shah|website=apnaorg.com|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\n==Marriage and children==\nHe was married to Zubaidah Akhter and was a loving husband and a caring father. He was blessed with his four sons and two daughters. One of his sons died as a teenager in a terrible accident while playing with fire. He was severely burnt and was admitted in the hospital for just shy of one year before his death. Of the other three sons, one went on to become an army officer, another a professional banker and the third an engineer. Daughters are married too. All of the kids emigrated to the [[United States]] in 2008. He never wanted to live anywhere else but with his Punjabi community, however he was convinced by his kids to live with them in the [[United States]]. He visited them in 2013 and stayed with his children and grandchildren for two years. In 2015, he decided to go back to his village in [[Pakistan]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Death and afterward==\nDeath finally caught up with him in the village when he developed a chest infection. He was brought to [[Fatima Memorial Hospital]] in [[Lahore]] but it was too late. At the hospital, after his operation, he was not able to recognize people nor could he speak well. He was buried near a friendly saint\u2019s tomb in Narang Mandi. May God bless his soul.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Published works==\nAll the books Sharif Sabir has edited -- [[Heer Ranjha|Heer Waris Shah]], complete poetry of [[Bulleh Shah]] and [[Sultan Bahu]] and [[Prince Saiful Malook and Badri Jamala|Saiful Malook]] of [[Mian Muhammad Bakhsh]] -- have one outstanding feature in common. All of them carry a glossary of difficult words. No other book in [[Punjabi literature|Punjabi Literature]], other than those written on the [[Guru Granth Sahib]], contain comprehensive glossaries like the ones found in the works he has edited. Following is a list of books he has authored, edited or translated:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Works by Sharif Sabir\n!Book\n!Original Author\n!Sabir's Contribution\n!Year\n|-\n|Kalaam\n|[[Fariduddin Ganjshakar|Baba Farid]]\n|Edited (Due Publication)\n|\n|-\n|[[Prince Saiful Malook and Badri Jamala|Saiful Malook]]\n|[[Mian Muhammad Bakhsh]]\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLVnJKcFB6dkdYM0E/view Edited]\n|\n|-\n|[[Heer Ranjha|Heer Waris Shah]]\n|[[Waris Shah]]\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLVVMtN2dpQXhaTlk/view Edited]\n|\n|-\n|[https://www.sultanbahoo.net/abyat/ Abyat-e-Bahoo]\n|[[Sultan Bahu]]\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLN3NlVlc2azhfMEU/view Edited]\n|\n|-\n|[[Bulleh Shah]]\n|[[Bulleh Shah]]\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/1mLoCPnL1tt9GBJzzScwTpRieyUYQTODR/view Edited]\n|\n|-\n|Farsi Kalam\n|[https://www.facebook.com/Hafizsufimuhammadafzal/ Sufi Muhammad Afzal Faqeer]\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLZG5uZDdfOUVhTW8/view Translated]\n|\n|-\n|[[Puran Bhagat]]\n|[[Qadir Yar]]\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLQ042bXFaZ0M2ZDQ/view Translated]\n|\n|-\n|[[Kashf ul Mahjoob]]\n|[[Ali Hujwiri]]\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLYmQ4cWh1cmtjR1E/view Translated]\n|\n|-\n|[[Gulistan (book)|Gulistan]] and [[Bustan (book)|Bustan]]\n|[[Saadi Shirazi]]\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLcVY2QXhBQndFWFU/view Translated]\n|\n|-\n|Hatkoray\n|Sharif Sabir\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLdFpNc05xQzlVVDg/view Authored]\n|\n|-\n|Baghawat\n|Sharif Sabir\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLRnBfRmZaV2lyWHc/view Authored]\n|\n|-\n|Punjabi Drama\n|Sharif Sabir\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLZEZpZG9hcGs2Q3M/view Authored]\n|\n|-\n|Autobiography\n|Sharif Sabir\n|[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLQVRjQ1FSMGFwX1k/view Authored]\n|\n|}\n\n==Honours, decorations, awards and distinctions==\nHe was given the [[Pride of Performance]] and a paltry sum of Rs 70,000 for his monumental work [[Heer Ranjha|Heer Waris Shah]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://apnaorg.com/prose-content/articles-by-writers/Nadir-Ali/page-1/article-7/index.html|title=Victim of ignorance|website=apnaorg.com|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5vHzQXL_PGLQVRjQ1FSMGFwX1k/view Autobiography in Punjabi]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sabir, Sharif}}\n\n\n\n\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Pakistani philosophers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani poets]]\n[[Category:Punjabi poets]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control, addedorphantag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sharif_Sabir"}
{"title_page": "Hume Babington (clergyman)", "text_new": "[[File:RevHumeBabington.png|thumb|Rev. Hume Babington (1804-1886)]]\n\n[[The Reverend|The Rev.]] '''Hume Babington''' (1 September 1804 - 23 January 1886) was a [[Church of Ireland]] clergyman, serving as the [[Rector (ecclesiastical)#Anglican churches|rector]] at Moviddy, Co Cork, for 53 years from 1833-1886, and a proponent of [[secular education]] in Ireland<ref name=\"HB1\">[http://kilmurrymuseum.ie/Articles/kilmurry-hidden-gems-tour-notes-heritage-week-2017/ Rev. Hume Babington]</ref>.\n\n== Early life ==\nHe was born in 1804 to Rev. Richard [[Babington family#Babington family of Ireland|Babington]] and his wife Mary Boyle, both members of the [[Anglo-Irish people|Anglo-Irish]] [[landed gentry]]<ref name=\"ILG Bab\">Burke's Landed Gentry of Ireland, 1958, 4th Edition by [[L. G. Pine]], [[Burke's Peerage]]: 'Babington of Creevagh', pg 42'</ref><ref name=\"ILG Boyle\">Burke's Landed Gentry of Ireland, 1958, 4th Edition by [[L. G. Pine]], [[Burke's Peerage]]: 'Boyle of Desart'</ref>. His father, the rector of Lower Comber (Diocese of Derry), led an extravagant lifestyle and is said to have left debts of \u00a340,000 on his death in 1831, aged 66, equivalent to some \u00a34.1 million as of 2019<ref name=\"Inf\">https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/monetary-policy/inflation/inflation-calculator</ref><ref name=\"ABB Memoirs\">'Personal Reminisces of [[Anthony Babington (politician)|Sir Anthony Babington, Q.C.]]'</ref>. His father's debt was paid off by his two brothers Richard (1795-1870) and Anthony of Creevagh (1800-1869) between them<ref name=\"ABB Memoirs\"></ref>. Another brother was Major-General [[William Babington (East India Company officer)|William Babington]]<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>.\n\nHe was educated at [[Trinity College, Dublin]].\n\n== Life as a clergyman ==\nHe began his career as a curate of Lower Cumber, where his father was rector, in 1827. He became rector of Moviddy in 1833, aged 29. As rector, Hume carried out improvements worth \u00a3166,766 as of 2019<ref name=\"Inf\"></ref>. As a clergyman he was part of a wave towards secular education in Ireland in the 1800s. In this capacity he is remembered as a 'very forward thinking individual'<ref name=\"HB1\"></ref>. Hume was one of the signatories of a progressive booklet titled 'Declaration in Favour of United Secular Education in Ireland' in 1866<ref name=\"Booklet\">[https://ptfs-oireachtas.s3.amazonaws.com/DriveF/Data/Library3/Library3/DCT108001.pdf 'Declaration in Favour of a United Secular Education in Ireland']</ref>. The declaration noted, on behalf of the united Church of England and Ireland, 'We entirely admit the justice and policy of the rule which protects scholars from interference with their religious principles and thus enables members of different denominations, to receive together in harmony and peace, the benefits of a good education'<ref name=\"Booklet\"></ref>.\n\nHe was also, notably, in 1843, an addressee of the 'Crookstown letter', a famous incident at the time covered by the Cork Examiner and Cork Commercial Courier<ref name=\"HB1\"></ref>. He published, in the Cork Constitution, the contents of a threatening letter he had received ('the Crookstown notice'), in which it threatened, among others, Hume Babington, with murder if he did not become a repealer of the [[Acts of Union 1800|Act of Union 1801]] and with making a bonfire of hay in his farmyard if he did not show the letter to its other addresses<ref name=\"HB1\"></ref>. The letter was alleged to have been written by a [[Roman Catholic]] resident of [[Crookstown, County Cork|Crookstown]]. The Roman Catholic parish priest, Fr Daly, and parishioners refuted the allegation that the letter had been authored by a Roman Catholic and claimed that, conversely, the letter was an invention of a local [[Protestant]] who wrote 'repeal or die' on the Crookstown Bridge. A local magistrate, JB Warren, to whom the letter had also been addressed, pledged to carry out an investigation but Hume Babington did not hand over the original letter, causing the local Roman Catholic population to regard Babington's publication of the letter in the press as 'prejudiced, premature and defamatory of the character of the people whose industry he derives his income'<ref name=\"HB1\"></ref>. Babington stated that he had always been on friendly terms with the Roman Catholic parish priest and his Roman Catholic parishioners and had no intention of offending them but was in fact pushed to publish it by local magistrates. He continued as rector of Moviddy for another 43 years following this incident.\n\nHe was also involved with the Society for Promoting the Education of the Poor of Ireland<ref name=\"SPEPI\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=t3QWAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA88&lpg=RA1-PA88&dq=Society+for+Promoting+the+Education+of+the+Poor+of+ireland+hume+babington&source=bl&ots=Sp11RTqkBM&sig=ACfU3U35jSUTvglIfwFUSAM78Fl0-WLvKA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiryPWJ29noAhUXHMAKHfqfCk4Q6AEwAHoECAsQKQ#v=onepage&q&f=false Bentham, C. (1824). Twelfth Report of the Society for Promoting the Education of the Poor of Ireland, Vol 12-14, p. 88.]</ref>.\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe married, in 1836, Esther, daughter of Richard Nettles, [[Esquire]], JP, of Nettleville, County Cork, with whom he had 5 sons and 8 daughters<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>:\n\n*Rev. Richard Babington (1837-29 September 1893), rector at Glendermot, Co. Londonderry, Ireland (father of [[Richard Babington (Dean of Cork)]])<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Anne Babington (27 August 1838-1873); she married Rev. George Herrick<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Caroline Mary Babington (4 December 1839-1840); unmarried <ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Captain James Boyle Babington, [[Royal Navy|RN]] (26 April 1841-19 July 1897), he married Elizabeth Blackley and emigrated to [[Vancouver, Canada]] around 1888 (father of Captain Hume Blackley Babington and Evoryna May Babington of Vancouver)<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Mary Babington (12 February 1842-1914); unmarried <ref name=\"ICR\">Ireland Civil Registration Indexes, 1845-1958</ref><ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Esther Elizabeth Babington (29 April 1843-31 August 1878); she married her cousin Richard Nettles, Esq., JP, of Nettleville, Co. Cork<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Caroline Sarah Anne Babington (8 March 1844-6 December 1935); unmarried <ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref><ref name=\"EWW\">England and Wales, National Index of Wills and Administrations, 1858-1957</ref>\n*Angel Babington (14 June 1845-d.); she married Rev. Richard Bathoe Jones (grandmother of [[Charles Phibbs Jones|General Sir Charles Jones]] and [[Edward Warburton Jones|Sir Edward Warburton Jones]] among others)<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Georgina Kingsley Babington (13 July 1846-5 April 1938); unmarried <ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref><ref name=\"EWW\"></ref>\n*Robert Babington (6 July 1847-d.)<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Hume Babington, [[Esquire|Esq.]], JP, of Creevagh, Co. Londonderry, Ireland (15 July 1848 - 6 June 1925); inherited the Creevagh estate, from his uncle Anthony, aged 21 in 1869 (father of [[Anthony Babington (politician)|Sir Anthony Babington]])<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Helen Frances Babington (17 August 1850-28 December 1934); unmarried <ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref><ref name=\"EWW\"></ref>\n*David Robert Babington (17 August 1852-17 May 1902), solicitor, married Mary [[Le Fanu]] on 12 November 1878 (grandfather of [[Robert Babington]])<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n\nHe died 23 January 1886 at Moviddy Rectory, Co. Cork, aged 81. He is buried with his wife, Esther, who died on 29 August 1878, aged 70<ref name=\"HG\">[https://historicgraves.com/st-helen-s-moviddy-crookstown/co-movi-0012/grave Hume and Esther Babington, St Helen's, Moviddy, Crookstown]</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Babington, Hume}}\n[[Category: 1804 births]]\n[[Category: 1886 deaths]]\n[[Category: Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category: Church of Ireland clergy]]\n[[Category: Babington family|Hume]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:RevHumeBabington.png|thumb|Rev. Hume Babington (1804-1886)]]\n\n[[The Reverend|The Rev.]] '''Hume Babington''' (1 September 1804 - 23 January 1886) was a [[Church of Ireland]] clergyman, serving as the [[Rector (ecclesiastical)#Anglican churches|rector]] at Moviddy, Co Cork, for 53 years from 1833-1886, and a proponent of [[secular education]] in Ireland<ref name=\"HB1\">[http://kilmurrymuseum.ie/Articles/kilmurry-hidden-gems-tour-notes-heritage-week-2017/ Rev. Hume Babington]</ref>.\n\n== Early life ==\nHe was born in 1804 to Rev. Richard [[Babington family#Babington family of Ireland|Babington]] and his wife Mary Boyle, both members of the [[Anglo-Irish people|Anglo-Irish]] [[landed gentry]]<ref name=\"ILG Bab\">Burke's Landed Gentry of Ireland, 1958, 4th Edition by [[L. G. Pine]], [[Burke's Peerage]]: 'Babington of Creevagh', pg 42'</ref><ref name=\"ILG Boyle\">Burke's Landed Gentry of Ireland, 1958, 4th Edition by [[L. G. Pine]], [[Burke's Peerage]]: 'Boyle of Desart'</ref>. His father, the rector of Lower Comber (Diocese of Derry), led an extravagant lifestyle and is said to have left debts of \u00a340,000 on his death in 1831, aged 66, equivalent to some \u00a34.1 million as of 2019<ref name=\"Inf\">https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/monetary-policy/inflation/inflation-calculator</ref><ref name=\"ABB Memoirs\">'Personal Reminisces of [[Anthony Babington (politician)|Sir Anthony Babington, Q.C.]]'</ref>. His father's debt was paid off by his two brothers Richard (1795-1870) and Anthony of Creevagh (1800-1869) between them<ref name=\"ABB Memoirs\"></ref>.\n\nHe was educated at [[Trinity College, Dublin]].\n\n== Life as a clergyman ==\nHe began his career as a curate of Lower Cumber, where his father was rector, in 1827. He became rector of Moviddy in 1833, aged 29. As rector, Hume carried out improvements worth \u00a3166,766 as of 2019<ref name=\"Inf\"></ref>. As a clergyman he was part of a wave towards secular education in Ireland in the 1800s. In this capacity he is remembered as a 'very forward thinking individual'<ref name=\"HB1\"></ref>. Hume was one of the signatories of a progressive booklet titled 'Declaration in Favour of United Secular Education in Ireland' in 1866<ref name=\"Booklet\">[https://ptfs-oireachtas.s3.amazonaws.com/DriveF/Data/Library3/Library3/DCT108001.pdf 'Declaration in Favour of a United Secular Education in Ireland']</ref>. The declaration noted, on behalf of the united Church of England and Ireland, 'We entirely admit the justice and policy of the rule which protects scholars from interference with their religious principles and thus enables members of different denominations, to receive together in harmony and peace, the benefits of a good education'<ref name=\"Booklet\"></ref>.\n\nHe was also, notably, in 1843, an addressee of the 'Crookstown letter', a famous incident at the time covered by the Cork Examiner and Cork Commercial Courier<ref name=\"HB1\"></ref>. He published, in the Cork Constitution, the contents of a threatening letter he had received ('the Crookstown notice'), in which it threatened, among others, Hume Babington, with murder if he did not become a repealer of the [[Acts of Union 1800|Act of Union 1801]] and with making a bonfire of hay in his farmyard if he did not show the letter to its other addresses<ref name=\"HB1\"></ref>. The letter was alleged to have been written by a [[Roman Catholic]] resident of [[Crookstown, County Cork|Crookstown]]. The Roman Catholic parish priest, Fr Daly, and parishioners refuted the allegation that the letter had been authored by a Roman Catholic and claimed that, conversely, the letter was an invention of a local [[Protestant]] who wrote 'repeal or die' on the Crookstown Bridge. A local magistrate, JB Warren, to whom the letter had also been addressed, pledged to carry out an investigation but Hume Babington did not hand over the original letter, causing the local Roman Catholic population to regard Babington's publication of the letter in the press as 'prejudiced, premature and defamatory of the character of the people whose industry he derives his income'<ref name=\"HB1\"></ref>. Babington stated that he had always been on friendly terms with the Roman Catholic parish priest and his Roman Catholic parishioners and had no intention of offending them but was in fact pushed to publish it by local magistrates. He continued as rector of Moviddy for another 43 years following this incident.\n\nHe was also involved with the Society for Promoting the Education of the Poor of Ireland<ref name=\"SPEPI\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=t3QWAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA88&lpg=RA1-PA88&dq=Society+for+Promoting+the+Education+of+the+Poor+of+ireland+hume+babington&source=bl&ots=Sp11RTqkBM&sig=ACfU3U35jSUTvglIfwFUSAM78Fl0-WLvKA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiryPWJ29noAhUXHMAKHfqfCk4Q6AEwAHoECAsQKQ#v=onepage&q&f=false Bentham, C. (1824). Twelfth Report of the Society for Promoting the Education of the Poor of Ireland, Vol 12-14, p. 88.]</ref>.\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe married, in 1836, Esther, daughter of Richard Nettles, [[Esquire]], JP, of Nettleville, County Cork, with whom he had 5 sons and 8 daughters<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>:\n\n*Rev. Richard Babington (1837-29 September 1893), rector at Glendermot, Co. Londonderry, Ireland (father of [[Richard Babington (Dean of Cork)]])<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Anne Babington (27 August 1838-1873); she married Rev. George Herrick<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Caroline Mary Babington (4 December 1839-1840); unmarried <ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Captain James Boyle Babington, [[Royal Navy|RN]] (26 April 1841-19 July 1897), he married Elizabeth Blackley and emigrated to [[Vancouver, Canada]] around 1888 (father of Captain Hume Blackley Babington and Evoryna May Babington of Vancouver)<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Mary Babington (12 February 1842-1914); unmarried <ref name=\"ICR\">Ireland Civil Registration Indexes, 1845-1958</ref><ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Esther Elizabeth Babington (29 April 1843-31 August 1878); she married her cousin Richard Nettles, Esq., JP, of Nettleville, Co. Cork<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Caroline Sarah Anne Babington (8 March 1844-6 December 1935); unmarried <ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref><ref name=\"EWW\">England and Wales, National Index of Wills and Administrations, 1858-1957</ref>\n*Angel Babington (14 June 1845-d.); she married Rev. Richard Bathoe Jones (grandmother of [[Charles Phibbs Jones|General Sir Charles Jones]] and [[Edward Warburton Jones|Sir Edward Warburton Jones]] among others)<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Georgina Kingsley Babington (13 July 1846-5 April 1938); unmarried <ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref><ref name=\"EWW\"></ref>\n*Robert Babington (6 July 1847-d.)<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Hume Babington, [[Esquire|Esq.]], JP, of Creevagh, Co. Londonderry, Ireland (15 July 1848 - 6 June 1925); inherited the Creevagh estate, from his uncle Anthony, aged 21 in 1869 (father of [[Anthony Babington (politician)|Sir Anthony Babington]])<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n*Helen Frances Babington (17 August 1850-28 December 1934); unmarried <ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref><ref name=\"EWW\"></ref>\n*David Robert Babington (17 August 1852-17 May 1902), solicitor, married Mary [[Le Fanu]] on 12 November 1878 (grandfather of [[Robert Babington]])<ref name=\"ILG Bab\"></ref>\n\nHe died 23 January 1886 at Moviddy Rectory, Co. Cork, aged 81. He is buried with his wife, Esther, who died on 29 August 1878, aged 70<ref name=\"HG\">[https://historicgraves.com/st-helen-s-moviddy-crookstown/co-movi-0012/grave Hume and Esther Babington, St Helen's, Moviddy, Crookstown]</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Babington, Hume}}\n[[Category: 1804 births]]\n[[Category: 1886 deaths]]\n[[Category: Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category: Church of Ireland clergy]]\n[[Category: Babington family|Hume]]\n